LI). The collection investigates a range of themes including linguistic relativity, the possible contributions of neurolinguistics, the problem of cognitive development and the role of the frequency of structures in acquisition from distinct, overlapping and complementary perspectives. Chapters focusing on vocabulary, morphosyntactic categories, semantic structures, and phonetic and phonological structures feature in the volume, as do over 20 languages, in order to offer new insights into both theoretical and empirical issues in CLI, including the consequences of great or little similarity in structures between languages. The relevance of CLI research for teaching is discussed in a number of chapters, as is the phenomenon of multilingualism. The collection will appeal to researchers, graduate and postgraduate students, teachers and professionals interested in the field of CLI in SLA.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aInteraction analysis in education. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aLanguages in contact. 0aMulticultural education. 0aSecond language acquisitionxStudy and teaching. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aApplied cognitive linguistics.  aCLI.  aCrosslinguistic influence.  aLinguistic relativity.  aMultilingual transfer.  aNeurolinguistics.  aSLA.  alanguage learning.  atransfer.1 aAlonso Alonso, Rosa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlonso, Rosa Alonso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArabski, Janusz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAthanosopoulos, Panos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoutonnet, Bastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadierno, Teresa, 